# Instrument-Sampler Рђћ Technical Specification

## Purpose

Application that captures live audio from an acoustic instrument, provides real-time monophonic MIDI feedback to the performer, records the session, and then produces full polyphonic MIDI transcription and timbre-cloned audio as post-processing outputs Рђћ all routed into FL Studio.

## Pipeline Architecture

The system operates in two modes: a **live path** for low-latency feedback during performance, and a **post-recording path** for high-quality offline processing.

```
Mic Рєњ [Ingestion] Рєњ Dispatcher РћђРћгРћђРєњ [Live Analysis (aubio)] Рєњ MIDI Рєњ FL Studio (virtual MIDI port)
                                 РћћРћђРєњ [WAV Recorder] Рєњ .wav file РћђРћгРћђРєњ [Transcription (basic-pitch)] Рєњ .mid file Рєњ FL Studio (import)
                                                                   РћћРћђРєњ [Timbre Cloning (RAVE/DDSP)] Рєњ .wav file Рєњ FL Studio (import)
```

### Stage 1 Рђћ Ingestion

Stream real-time audio buffers from the system input device using `sounddevice` (PortAudio). Callback-based `sd.InputStream` feeds an explicit `Dispatcher` that fans out each audio frame to all subscribed consumer queues. Target: 44100 Hz, float32, mono.

### Stage 2 Рђћ Live Analysis

`aubio` performs real-time onset detection and monophonic YIN pitch tracking on each audio frame as it arrives from the dispatcher. Detected onsets immediately emit `mido.Message` objects to the virtual MIDI port. This path is monophonic and approximate Рђћ its purpose is performer feedback, not archival transcription.

### Stage 3 Рђћ Recording

A WAV recorder consumer subscribes to the dispatcher and writes every audio frame to a `.wav` file on disk. This recorded file is the input for both post-processing stages.

### Stage 4 Рђћ Post-Processing: Transcription

After recording completes, Spotify `basic-pitch` (CNN, ONNX backend) runs on the full `.wav` file via its standard `predict()` API. It produces a polyphonic MIDI file with accurate note boundaries, velocities, and pitch bends. No streaming hacks or chunk stitching required.

### Stage 5 Рђћ Post-Processing: Timbre Cloning

After recording completes, **RAVE** (primary) or **DDSP** (fallback) processes the full `.wav` file to synthesize audio that recreates the instrument's acoustic texture. Output is a `.wav` file at 44.1 kHz.

### Stage 6 Рђћ The Bridge

- **Live MIDI routing**: `mido` with `python-rtmidi` backend opens a virtual MIDI output port fed by the live aubio analyzer. FL Studio reads from this port in real time. On Windows, `loopMIDI` provides the virtual port.
- **Post-processing file export**: The transcription stage writes a `.mid` file and the timbre cloning stage writes a `.wav` file. Both are imported into FL Studio after the session.

## Dependencies (Split by Mode)

| Group | File | Packages |
|---|---|---|
| Live runtime | `requirements.txt` | `sounddevice`, `numpy`, `aubio` (or `aubio-ledfx`), `mido`, `python-rtmidi`, `scipy` |
| Post-processing | `requirements-post.txt` | `basic-pitch[onnx]`, `onnxruntime`, `librosa` |
| Model training | `requirements-train.txt` | `acids-rave`, `torch`, `torchaudio` (or `ddsp`, `tensorflow` for DDSP fallback) |

## Key Constraints

| Constraint | Value |
|---|---|
| Python version | 3.11 |
| Live-path latency | < 50 ms end-to-end (ingestion Рєњ aubio Рєњ MIDI send) |
| Post-processing latency | Offline; no real-time constraint |
| Architecture | Live path is streaming-first; post-processing operates on complete files |
| Primary OS | macOS (native virtual MIDI, BlackHole for future live audio); Windows via loopMIDI + VB-Cable |
